# Function Ordering

Within a file, declare the main/entry-point function first, then the helpers it calls below it. Readers should see the top-level flow before the supporting details.

This applies to both exported entry points and private module-scope functions that orchestrate other helpers.

```ts
// ❌ BAD — helpers before the function that calls them
function parseManifest(text: string): Manifest { /* ... */ }
function defineProxy(cls: ElementConstructor): string { /* ... */ }

export async function loadComponent(url: string): Promise<string> {
  const text = await fetch(url).then(r => r.text());
  const manifest = parseManifest(text);
  return defineProxy(manifest.cls);
}
```

```ts
// ✅ GOOD — entry point first, helpers below
export async function loadComponent(url: string): Promise<string> {
  const text = await fetch(url).then(r => r.text());
  const manifest = parseManifest(text);
  return defineProxy(manifest.cls);
}

function parseManifest(text: string): Manifest { /* ... */ }
function defineProxy(cls: ElementConstructor): string { /* ... */ }
```

Exceptions: hoisted constants, type aliases, and imports stay at the top of the file. Class methods are ordered by the same rule — public/entry methods above the private helpers they call.
